Name: Robin Frankham
Comment:
I've come across an anomaly that I can't get my head around... can anyone give a reason for this.

At 3.10.18 in the tutorial there is an exercise concerning the 'ORDER BY' statment.

If I write the query as :

1 SELECT * 
2 FROM order_items 
3 WHERE order_id = 2
4 ORDER BY quantity * unit_price 

I get records with product_id 6, 4 & 1 in that order - (ascending order)

If I write the query as :

1 SELECT * 
2 FROM order_items 
3 WHERE order_id = 2
4 ORDER BY quantity * unit_price DESC

I get records with product_id 1, 4 & 6 in that order - (descending order) - So far so good

If I write:

1 SELECT *, quantity * unit_price as 'Total Cost'
2 FROM order_items 
3 WHERE order_id = 2
4 ORDER BY  'Total Cost' DESC

I get records with product_id 1, 4 & 6 in that order - (descending order) - again fine

If I write:

1 SELECT *, quantity * unit_price as 'Total Cost'
2 FROM order_items 
3 WHERE order_id = 2
4 ORDER BY  'Total Cost'

I still records with product_id 1, 4 & 6 in that order - (descending order) - Aargh!... Surely, line 4 should cause the result to be in ascending order?

Am I doing something wrong? If so what?... is this an anomaly in SQL? If so, are there any others I should know about?

Rob F

Name: Nicolae Zamfir
Comment:
first exercise from REGEXP tutorial is :
SELECT *
FROM customers
WHERE first_name IN ('AMBUR','ELKA')

You are asking to display only the firs names with AMBUR or ELKA. Your REGEXP command will display all first name who contains those two words, not the ones who are exactly those two words. Using the IN you will filter only for those two, as per request.

Name: crystal villanueva
Comment:
at 2:05, I did another solution for outer joining multiple tables: 

```select 
    o.order_date, 
    o.order_id, 
    c.first_name as customer, 
    s.name as "shipper", 
(case when o.status = 1 then "Processed" else "Shipped" end) as status 
from orders o 
left join shippers s on o.shipper_id = s.shipper_id 
join customers c on c.customer_id = o.customer_id
order by o.status asc;``` 

I just wanted to throw this out there in case someone wanted to use it !
